    "    display(IPImage(path))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a5371d91",
   "source": "## 8. Label free failure detection anywhere in the world\n\nThe model can score aerial imagery from any place on earth even though no labels exist there. First fit_ood.py builds a reference of what the LoveDA training tiles look like in backbone feature space. Then scan_failures.py takes any folder of images, slides a window over each one at native resolution so the 0.3 m ground sample distance is preserved, and writes failure heatmaps plus a ranking of the least trustworthy images. High entropy or margin risk marks ambiguous pixels. A high novelty score marks scenes unlike the training data, where even confident predictions deserve doubt.\n\nThe demo below scans a few LoveDA validation images, which are in domain, so expect low novelty. To scan your own imagery from anywhere, upload aerial tiles near 0.3 m per pixel into data/world_samples. No label is needed.",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "id": "b56e420c",
   "source": "!python scripts/fit_ood.py --checkpoint results/loveda_deeplabv3/checkpoints/best.pth --num-images 300",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "id": "1626acd4",
   "source": "import glob, os, shutil\nos.makedirs(\"data/world_samples\", exist_ok=True)\nfor path in sorted(glob.glob(\"data/raw/LoveDA/Val/Urban/images_png/*.png\"))[:6]:\n    shutil.copy(path, \"data/world_samples\")\n# Drop your own aerial tiles into data/world_samples to scan any place on earth.\n\n!python scripts/scan_failures.py --checkpoint results/loveda_deeplabv3/checkpoints/best.pth --images data/world_samples --output-dir results/loveda_deeplabv3/scan\n\nimport pandas as pd\nfrom IPython.display import Image as IPImage, display\ndisplay(pd.read_csv(\"results/loveda_deeplabv3/scan/rankings.csv\"))\nfor path in sorted(glob.glob(\"results/loveda_deeplabv3/scan/panels/*.png\"))[:3]:\n    display(IPImage(path))",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "84942ea0",
   "source": "## 9. Validate the failure signals against real labels\n\nThe failure maps above are only worth trusting if they truly predict errors. This check runs the signals on the labeled validation split and measures how well each one ranks wrong pixels above correct ones. AUROC of 0.5 is chance and 1.0 is perfect. It also reports how well the per image mean signal tracks the true per image error rate.\n\nThis first cell runs in domain on LoveDA validation, which mostly proves the plumbing. The cross domain cell after it is the test that matters.",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "id": "6d59141a",
   "source": "!python scripts/validate_signals.py --checkpoint results/loveda_deeplabv3/checkpoints/best.pth --limit 300\n\nimport json\nfrom IPython.display import Image as IPImage, display\nbase = \"results/loveda_deeplabv3/validation/loveda_val\"\nprint(json.dumps(json.load(open(base + \"/metrics.json\"))[\"pixel\"], indent=2))\nfor name in [\"risk_coverage.png\", \"failure_deciles.png\", \"failure_vs_error.png\"]:\n    display(IPImage(base + \"/\" + name))",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c12bfe08",
   "source": "### Cross domain test on ISPRS Potsdam\n\nThis is the real proof. The model trained on Chinese imagery while Potsdam is German urban imagery at 0.05 m per pixel, so the geography, the sensor and the scene style all change at once. The cell below pulls the ISPRS benchmark from a public Kaggle mirror, cuts the 38 orthophotos into 2304 pixel patches so the resized network input lands back at 0.3 m per pixel, then reruns the validation with the Potsdam class mapping and the LoveDA run above as the novelty baseline. Run the LoveDA cell first since its per_image.csv is the baseline here. If AUROC and the correlations stay clearly above chance, the label free signals survive domain shift.",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "id": "34437d21",
   "source": "import kagglehub\nsrc = kagglehub.dataset_download(\"aletbm/urban-segmentation-isprs\")\nprint(\"dataset at\", src)\n\n!python scripts/prepare_potsdam.py --images \"{src}/Potsdam/Images\" --labels \"{src}/Potsdam/Labels\" --output data/raw/PotsdamPatches\n\n!python scripts/validate_signals.py --checkpoint results/loveda_deeplabv3/checkpoints/best.pth --set dataset.name=potsdam dataset.root=data/raw/PotsdamPatches --label-map potsdam_to_loveda --baseline-csv results/loveda_deeplabv3/validation/loveda_val/per_image.csv\n\nimport json\nfrom IPython.display import Image as IPImage, display\nbase = \"results/loveda_deeplabv3/validation/potsdam_val\"\nprint(json.dumps(json.load(open(base + \"/metrics.json\"))[\"pixel\"], indent=2))\nfor name in [\"risk_coverage.png\", \"failure_deciles.png\", \"failure_vs_error.png\", \"novelty_hist.png\"]:\n    display(IPImage(base + \"/\" + name))",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
